<font color=#6F6F6F>(1/23/04 1:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=148.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   &quot;Threat and Promise&quot;</span><hr size=1> I would definitely feel cheated if it were announced that one were falling in tomorrow, and they'd let me keep working to pay taxes and bills instead of taking a holiday for the last few days of life's existence!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; In the space out to about 200 million km, it has so far found about 650 &quot;monsters&quot; - none of which have orbits that pose a threat to the Earth. There is possibly a similar figure of undiscovered one-km-plus-sized rocks in the same region of space that have yet to be tracked down.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Another mis-statement.<br>
Many if not all of these NEAs have orbits which pose definite threats -they just haven't found any that are predicted to hit Earth in the next few centuries which is all they can accurately predict.<br>
 By definition, being in Earth-crossing orbits means that they're threats. The lifetime of these types of rocks is only a few hundred million years. The definition of the end of that lifetime is being swept up by impacting Earth, and the numbers of ones found, the rate they're replenished by perturbations from Jupiter and such, indicates that there's a never-ending stream of them. The impact record of the Earth &amp; Moon show these numbers out. It's only a matter of time.<br>
<br>
It's not all about the kilometer-scale global killers either. A 250 meter rock would impact like several gigatons of TNT, laying waste to continents. If they hit on water (75% chance) they raise global tsunamis up to 80 meters tall, which may increase the damage and loss.<br>
The one that made the crater in Arizona was undetctable to today's network, and probably these ~60 meter rocks will never be found. They're just too small. We have picked up rocks down to 3 meters across, but only by luck as it zips past a few hundred thousand Km away. One of these truck-sized rocks carrries several kilotons of energy -a neat city-killer.<br>
The Arizona impact would have scorched a path hundreds of km across as it entered the atmosphere, then the impact would have wiped out everything within several hundred km.<br>
<br>
While comets approaching out of the Sun are a danger, as the article said, these little city-killers and continent smashers are the worse threats -there should be 100 times as many of these in Earth-crossing orbits as there are km scale dinosaur killers.<br>
We see them all the time skipping out of the atmosphere. They'll streak past, making a high fireball, possibly dropping sonic booms at close approach, before their trajectory takes them back out. Only a few tens of km make the difference between detonating or skipping out.<br>
<br>
The ones in Earth-like orbits are the worst. They'll come in with low relative speeds -by definition, they are moving in orbits very like Earth's. We're just lucky that lots of them are soft carbonaceous bits that crumble high up, making these detonation flashes. Stones or metal fragments this size on these trajectories, are the ones which will survive coming through the atmosphere to hit the ground or water.<br>
 Very nearly Earth-like orbits mean that we can't see them, either, since they'll zip past too fast for some detectors, or they're too close to the dawn terminator line.<br>
<br>
The things to do is to place lots of these detectors in orbit and other orbits near Earth. Anyhere around the Earth-Moon system, or especially out at the Earth-Sun L-1,4or5 points would be good.<br>
<br>
A 200 meter stony rock (the most common kind, and several billion of them should be out there.) would be nice. It'll be in one of those orbits which are nearly certain to hit us some day, and also getting to them and bringing stuff back from them would take a fraction of the rocketry it takes to get to our Moon or to Mars.<br>
Land a mining/orbit changing base on it, and change the crews out every year or so (The sooner they can set up shielded spinning habitats the better). Send back a few thousand tons of refined ices at the first opportunity (launching windows for getting back to Earth occur a few times a year, and last months for very small delta-V).<br>
Every few years, a load of ices comes back with a crew return, and more stuff is put at the rock, as it's being slowly brought back to HEEO to make a new small, temporary moon.<br>
This pays back the investment sooner (the asteroid threat is not a budget drain nightmare, but an great investment), makes Mars exploration better, and builds up our capabilities to go back out to get others and bring them back, under control, so we can use up the supply of Earth-threatening impactors. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 1/23/04 1:46 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3>Asteroid Watch & General Astronomy</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.3p<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  